05077nam a22006255i 9780822391098DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223910987 a10.1515/97808223910982doi  a(DE-B1597)553770  a(OCoLC)1200080083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3487.B7bD468 2009 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aDent, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRiver of Tears :bCountry Music, Memory, and Modernity in Brazil /cAlexander Dent. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b5 figures, 3 tables, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection : 3300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Rural Music, Intimacy, and Memory -- t1 What Counts as ‘‘Country’’? Rural Performativity in the Twentieth Century -- t2 Country Brothers: Kinship as Chronotope -- t3 Mixture, Sadness, and Intimacy in the Brazilian Musical Field -- t4 Hick Dialogics: Experiencing the Play of Rural Genres -- t5 Teleologies of Rural Disappearance: Interpreting Rural Music -- t6 Digital Droplets and Analogue Flames: The Circulatory Matrices of Brazilian Country -- t7 Producing Rural Locality -- t8 Hicks of the World: The Country Cosmopolitan -- tConclusion: Postauthoritarian Memory and Rurality -- tNotes -- tMusical Works Cited -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRiver of Tears is the first ethnography of Brazilian country music, one of the most popular genres in Brazil yet least-known outside it. Beginning in the mid-1980s, commercial musical duos practicing música sertaneja reached beyond their home in Brazil’s central-southern region to become national bestsellers. Rodeo events revolving around country music came to rival soccer matches in attendance. A revival of folkloric rural music called música caipira, heralded as música sertaneja’s ancestor, also took shape. And all the while, large numbers of Brazilians in the central-south were moving to cities, using music to support the claim that their Brazil was first and foremost a rural nation.Since 1998, Alexander Sebastian Dent has analyzed rural music in the state of São Paulo, interviewing and spending time with listeners, musicians, songwriters, journalists, record-company owners, and radio hosts. Dent not only describes the production and reception of this music, he also explains why the genre experienced such tremendous growth as Brazil transitioned from an era of dictatorship to a period of intense neoliberal reform. Dent argues that rural genres reflect a widespread anxiety that change has been too radical and has come too fast. In defining their music as rural, Brazil’s country musicians—whose work circulates largely in cities—are criticizing an increasingly inescapable urban life characterized by suppressed emotions and an inattentiveness to the past. Their performances evoke a river of tears flowing through a landscape of loss—of love, of life in the countryside, and of man’s connections to the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCountry musicxPolitical aspectszBrazil. 0aCountry musicxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aCountry musiczBrazilxHistory and criticism. 0aMúsica sertanejaxPolitical aspectszBrazil. 0aMúsica sertanejaxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aMúsica sertanejazBrazilxHistory and criticism. 0aMúsica sertanejaxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aMúsica sertanejazBrazilxHistory and criticism. 0aMúsica sertanejazBrazilxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke Univer